caption: Favorite Indian spot.  The spicy goat is a winner

This place was absolutely delicious. Everything I ordered was absolutely wonderful. It's been so long since I had had Indian and Bombay fare exceeded my perception of what I remembered. My boyfriend, who went with me, wasn't a fan of Indian before we went here, but with the vegetarian options and watching me almost cry because of how good the Naan was, I think his mind was forever changed. The chai was delicious, even if admittedly smaller than expected. Naan is not pictured because I ordered it a while into the meal, but it was so soft and warm and wonderful. There was also a giant mural with Anthony Bourdain which really touched me. Please give this place a chance, it won't disappoint.

Mentioned it to the server but he didn't think it was no big deal so beware. I reported to the health department of dc so hopefully something will be done about it, for me I won't be visiting this restaurant again.

As name suggests Bombay.. first thing comes in my mind is misal pav... I went 15 miles just to have misal pav.. not at all worth. Highly dissatisfied and disappointed. In the name of misal pav i got moong dal with few pieces of farsan. This is a big disaster in the name of misal pav. Will never recommend this place.

Since moving to the DMV area I have been looking for a sufficient Thali since moving from NJ where there is a decent Indian presence. I was directed towards Bombay Street food 2 and was not let down.  I wish I could give half scores because they deserve a 3.5, not a 3. 😁  I like that they had alcoholic beverage options 😏☝🏽  I was let down because Samosa chaat is one of my favorites and it was not offered.  I say 3.5  because I’m NJ it’s staple for your Thali to come with Naan instead of being charged for it. Also, I can get 2 full Thalis for $22, not $35. 😐🙄  I was very pleased that you get 3 different meat options and 3 veggie options. I thought it was a little foolish to have such a small portion of rice, but they bought over more upon request. The flavors were good and full.
Every bit as good as what I ate in India

Yes yes yes, a real gem for sure! My partner and I just moved to the DMV from NJ, where we had a place we visited religiously for thali & let me tell you it’s a great close second. We got the Bombay thali for two ( consisted of 3 meats, lamb, goat and chicken ; three veggies, spinach, chickpeas and lentils, plus accompanying herbed yogurt, pineapple spicy chutney, and a pickled pepper side). The meats ; all incredibly tender and flavorful! The lamb was the star, for me, my partner said they could’ve eaten a whole bowl of just chickpeas. Everything was hot and fresh when it arrived to our table, and the service was great minus a small wait when we were originally seated.  The only critique I’d say is that naan should be included with the thali, as it’s a staple I’m used to accompanying my meal with no extra charge. But over all, we will be back! Pictures and more details are available on my food blog IG: @hungryhungryheaux, same for Facebook. Cheers 🍻!

Go eat there!!  Quick search for food near me after leaving the National Mall area, and decided to check out this place.  When you first walk in, the delicious smell and beautiful decor pull you right in.  I ordered the lunch special which was offered in vegetarian and non-vegetarian, both looked great, but I ordered the vegetarian with some garlic naan.  This dish was so fantastic, and was only about $12.  The other two people with me ordered off the menu and loved their food too.  If you have the means to get over to this restaurant, please do it. Definitely the place to come when looking for delicious Indian food! The space is super comfortable, service is friendly and it is located right on barracks row (8th street).  During lunch you can get a special for $14. The butter chicken platter is amazing and comes with lots of dips, dessert and naan. There is a ton on the platter and I honestly wasn't even sure what I was eating, but it was all delicious.  You can also order extra naan on the side which is always a must. They have a small kids menu with affordable options which is always nice.

Disclaimer: I have only ever gotten takeout from here. That said, their food is always fresh and delicious. I’ve tried a variety of items to this point highlighted by the Keema Pav and chicken tikka masala. Good levels of spice in all of their dishes as well. Service has always been prompt and friendly. If you’re looking for good, takeout Indian food then Bombay Street Food is the place to go.

This is my favorite restaurant in D.C.  Food: 10/10 Service: 10/10  Not only does the food come out super quick, it is some of the best Indian food I’ve ever had. Everything on the menu is amazing but my personal favorite is the paneer tikka masala. I have only found two places that do this dish right and bsf2 is one of them.

Awesome food and service. We visited dc for a long weekend and this was our first experience with Indian food, we’ll definitely be back. The waitress suggested that we order the $35 platter for 2 thali and we could not have been happier. It allows you to try all of their delicious food, you can order unlimited rice on the house and it comes with their delicious naan. The lamb and goat were our favorites. Definitely an awesome option for the price

I was so heartbroken when my favorite Indian joint on Barracks Row shut down. They had chicken tikka masala just the way I like it: creamy, rich, with some smoky goodness from the chicken. There’s lots of great Indian food in D.C., but when you find yours, it’s yours, y’know?  Well, you can never replace an old favorite, but you can find new favorites. This place is my new favorite! They’ve got that chicken tikka masala, but also a wonderfully savory gobi aloo, garlic naan that doesn’t skimp on the garlic, and just-right samosas. My wife swears by their chai. The chana masala has just the right amount of heat.  The decor is funky. The staff are friendly. The food is awesome!
Excellent food, excellent service. Totally outstanding.
Awesome service and great food! The chicken tikka masala, chicken tikka kabob, and mango lassi were delicious everyone at our table loved what they got. Will definitely be back!

The food is great. And deceptively a lot. I went with a friend and we split an order of garlic naan, veggie biryani, and lamb saag. We couldn’t finish and had leftovers! They don’t skimp in the lamb and the biryani is moist and tasty. They put chapati over the biryani which gives it this great steamy effect when they cut it open for you. Also the biryani is chock of veggies. The only thing I’d say I didn’t appreciate is they only give you one piece In the $4 order of garlic naan. Aside from that I’d say go back - we split the bill - $38.50 - and defiantly got our moneys worth in terms of quantity and quality. Yum.

Bombay Street Food is an Indian sit-down restaurant on Barracks Row. It's the restaurant's second location in the city (the first is in Columbia Heights). Here's why we enjoyed it:  1) Space: It's pretty big with outdoor patio seating and seating in two areas inside. The kitchen is open in the back so you can watch them back your food.  2) Food: It's tasty and the menu is diverse. They even have a kid's menu. My wife, toddler, and I ordered the butter chicken, two orders of naan, rice, mango chutney, and two glasses of chai for lunch. Everything was very tasty (the chai is the perfect balance of sweet and spicy) and it filled us up for only $33.  3) Service: The staff are very kind.  This may be our new go-to spot on Capitol Hill.

Looking forward to being a regular at this much needed addition to the Washington DC Indian food scene. As a native of New Delhi (SouthEx) I take my street food very seriously. I can definitely endorse the menu at Bombay Street Food as authentic to Indian tastes. Went there twice with family and friends, and in fact introduced a friend to Indian food for the first time there. Recommend starting with a Bhel Puri or Pav Bhaji, maybe some pakoras from the Monsoon section. The Veg and Non Veg thalis are a great way to experience all the different flavors and colors. Be sure to go for the raita or mango chutney if the food is too spicy (but my american friends had no issues with the spiciness). If you're willing to venture further into traditional indian dishes, you can't go wrong with the Chicken Biryani or the Butter Chicken. Be sure to finish off your gut busting meal with a cutting chai. In fact, order it twice.

Really delicious Indian food. They have a good variety of vegetarian and non-veg options. Food is very flavorful. I have had good experiences with the staff whenever I have been. A slight downside is that the beer list is mostly uninteresting but the food makes up for it.

This place is dynamite! Fantastic food with super authentic flavors. Lively and warm interior.  Attentive service.  Really hit all the high points.  The platter for two is an absolute steal at $35. There were a few kinks in the service that I'd normally be tempted to deduct a star for but I'm giving them the benefit of the doubt as they're new and what they lacked in experience was made up for by the sheer number of wait staff.  Also be warned the some of the dishes are HOT,  not a negative for me but perhaps for some.

I am a Hospitality and Tourism Graduate and I think I can give 5 Stars to this place. I will recommend this place to anyone. Please give it a try. It is not just another Indian Restaurant. - Namaskar Babu, BBA, MBA, MA (Hospitality and Tourism)
Delicious and good service .

Possibly the worst service I have ever seen anywhere, and that is saying something for an Indian restaurant. We had our water poured, then nothing. A few minutes later an Asian gentleman came over asked if we were ready to order. No drinks offered, not offering any help with the menu, just asked nervously if we were ready. We asked about the plater for two and and the spice level but all he could say was how everybody loved it. We took a chance and order it. 30 minutes later it arrived and an Indian gentleman brought it and then proceeded to walk off before my wife asked which one was the goat. He mumbled something but we could barley understand him. And good lord, the goat was very spice and full of small bones. Dinners should be warned. The lamb was extremely tough. You could not cut the lamb by the knife provided. It was chewy and tough. The butter chicken was overly spicy and yet lacked any complexity. While each dish looked like what they were supposed to, they lacked the multi layered flavor that very good Indian food should have. My wife was able to flag down a waitress and asked if we could have a couple of glasses of Cabernet Sauvignon. The waitress looked like she had no clue what we were asking for. My wife pointed to the wine list. Possibly the smallest and worse wine list I have ever seen. The waitress came back with two glasses of red wine, and when my wife said we had asked for two glasses of white wine. Her response was that we had asked for Cabernet and that is what the bartender gave her. She clearly didn’t know anything about wines. We just decided to keep the red. There was no table maintenance, nothing was cleared. Our water was refilled but no check back by anyone. And when the server brought us the check he didn’t clear the table or ask why nothing was eaten. We gave him our card, sat there with a dirty table until he cane back. Although the decor of the restaurant is cheerful enough, unfortunately the level of service and quality of food leaves much, much more to be desired. On dining strip where you world class restaurants like Rose’s and Ambar, this is really not acceptable. This place operates like third rate rate kebab house. It will probably become just another mediocre Indian restaurant like all the others.

Some Indian owners suffer from inferiority complex and like to treat people of Indian origin not the same as others . The Pav Bhaji was excellent. The Bhelpuri did not taste like authentic Bombay bhrl since there were no onions. It was also dry. The Kati roll was not moist like a Frankie in Bombay .  I wish them best of luck
